302 HORACE, ODES 111. xxi, xxii.

F rankness and hope and courage—these are thy gifts: Liber and Venus and the Graces—-these are thy companions. With thee and thern we will feast till daylight.

M. Valerius Messala Corvinus was at Athens with Horace in B.c. 42 and joined the army of Brutus. Subsequently he joined Octavian against Antony and commanded the centre of the Roman fleet at Actium. He afterwards commanded in Aquitania and was awarded a triumph in B.c. 27. He was a warm friend to literary men, especially to Tibullus and Propertius. It appears, from Servius’ note on Aeneid VI11. 31ο, that Maecenas wrote an imaginary conversation (called Symposz‘um) in which Messala was represented as extolling the virtues of wine. He is called disertus Messala in Ars Poet. 371.
